com.camerontec.catalys.util.data

Class AbstractTagValuesListIterator<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.camerontec.catalys.util.data.AbstractTagValuesListIterator<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - The underlying ITagValue storage mechanism. Must support indexed access.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Iterator<ITagValue>, ListIterator<ITagValue>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    TagValuesAsArrayIterator, TagValuesAsListIterator

    public abstract class AbstractTagValuesListIterator<T>
extends Object
implements ListIterator<ITagValue>
    Base class for all AbstractTagValues iterator implementations.

    AbstractTagValues implementations typically use different ITagValue storage mechanisms, however, they all support sequential access via iteration regardless of the underlying storage mechanism. This class abstracts away the underlying storage mechanism and provides java.util.ListIterator semantics over it.

    This class supports iterator reuse and initialization to indices other than the start or end of the underlying storage. See setTagValues(Object, int) and setIndex(int).

    This class allows (but does not force) the caller to specify a return value buffer to be used during iteration. See setBuffer(ITagValue). If an explicit return value buffer is not specified then the concrete implementation chooses the most appropriate buffer. This may be efficient in some cases, but in others may involve object creation. This class makes no guarantees either way.

    Neither this class nor any of its subclasses support remove(), add(ITagValue), or set(ITagValue). An java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException is thrown if any of these methods are called.

    Neither this class nor any of its subclass support concurrent modification from multiple threads. Further, no attempt is made to detect such conditions. Sufficient external mechanisms must be employed to protect against such concurrent modifications attempts else the results are undefined.

      • setBuffer

        public final void setBuffer(ITagValue buffer)
        Set the return value buffer.

        When not null the return value buffer is used to refer to successive elements in the underlying tag/value storage. When this is the case there is guarantee to be no object creation.

        When null, the concrete implementation determines the most efficient return value buffer. This may be efficient, however, no guarantees are given regarding object creation.

        Parameters:
        buffer - The return value buffer. May be null.
